A cheque bounce is a violation of Section 138 of the Negotiable Instruments Act of 1881 , punishable by a fine of up to double the value of the cheque , imprisonment for up to two years , or both . 
 What should you do if your right is violated ? 
 If you get payment via check and it bounces, you should immediately call a lawyer and serve a legal notice on the individual who is obliged to reimburse you . 
 If you do not obtain payment within 15 days of receiving the legal notice , you may pursue criminal charges against the individual , and he may be imprisoned as a result .

Section 125 of the Cr. P.C. states that parents (whether biological, adoptive, or stepfather or stepmother, senior citizen or not ) have the right to seek maintenance from their adult children . 
 
 What should you do if your right is violated? 

 Present adequate evidence to the court that your sons / daughters who are capable of supporting you have failed to do so. An application for maintenance may be made against any individual who is obligated to pay it .

According to Section 166 A of the Indian Penal Code, a police officer cannot decline to file an FIR . As an Indian citizen, you have the right to register an FIR for a cognizable offence, and a police officer who refuses to lodge the FIR is liable under Section 166A(c ) of the Indian Penal Code for committing a crime. According to the Supreme Court, in such circumstances, " the police officer will be subject to prosecution and punishment . " 

 How should this right be exercised ?

 Visit the police station (preferably close to the crime scene) and provide any relevant information to the officer in charge. In addition, Section 154 of the CrPC offers the informant the option of providing information verbally or in writing. 
 Note : According to Delhi Police guidelines, women have the option of filing a complaint by email or even by mail if they are unable to visit a police station. 

 What should you do if your right is violated?

 If the officer in charge declines to register a first information report concerning the occurrence of a cognizable criminal within his territorial authority in accordance with Section 154 ( 3 ) , the following procedures may be taken : 

 ( a ) Proceed to the Superintendent of Police: 

 With a written complaint, the informant can contact any senior official of the police, the Superintendent of Police, or the Commissioner of Police.
 If the Superintendent of Police believes that such information reveals the commission of a cognizable offence, he may conduct an inquiry personally or direct an investigation to be conducted by any police officer subordinate to him. 

 ( b ) Judicial Magistrate Complaint: 

 If, despite submitting a complaint to Senior Police officials, no FIR is lodged, the informant has the legal right to file a complaint with the Judicial Magistrate/ Metropolitan Magistrate under Section 156( 3 ) read with Section 190 of the criminal procedure, requesting that the FIR be registered by the police and an investigation into the matter to begin. 

 ( c ) Legal Recourse : 

 A Write Petition may be filed in the relevant High Court to seek damages / compensation if the Polices inactivity on the complaint /non - registration of FIR has resulted in the frustration / deprivation of life and liberty guaranteed by Article 21 of the Indian Constitution.

The Equal Remuneration Act of 1976 is a law that requires equal compensation for equal labour done by men and women. When two or more persons perform the same task under identical conditions, they are entitled to equal compensation. 
 
What should you do if your right is violated?

 When an employer violates these requirements, employees have the right to submit a complaint with the appropriate labour authorities. After validating the merits of the complaint, the competent labour authority may launch an investigation and take necessary action. Employers are obligated to keep registers including information about their employees pay.

According to the Motor Vehicle Act of 1988, if a traffic officer steals the key from your automobile or motorbike, you have the right to file a legal procedure against that traffic officer. 

 What should you do if your right is violated?

 If a traffic cop steals your vehicle keys for no apparent reason, snap photographs of the incident and file a complaint against that officer.

Under the RTI Act, any Indian person can seek information from any public authority, and the authority must respond as soon as possible or within thirty days. 

 If the petitioners life and liberty are at stake, the information must be delivered within 48 hours. 

 What should you do if your right is violated?

 Public employees who purposefully delay or block an application for information, or who purposefully offer erroneous or misleading information, may face penalties under RTI rules. It is critical to understand your legal rights as an Indian citizen in a country as varied and complicated as India. Not understanding your basic legal rights can have ramifications ranging from personal safety to work stability.

Did you know this is a startup or small business?

The first step in beginning any business is determining the kind and type of business. Founders must incorporate the company as a specified business kind, such as a sole proprietorship, a private limited company, a public limited company, a partnership, a limited liability partnership, and so on. It is critical to have this clarity from the start since it will be crucial to the entire vision and goals of the firm, both short and long-term. Each company kind has its own set of legal requirements and rules, which should be carefully considered before forming the firm. If you find yourself stuck in such a situation, we have specialists for you to help you out with it.

How do we process your information? We process your information to provide, improve, and administer our Services, communicate with you for security and fraud prevention, and comply with the law. We may also process your information for other purposes with your consent. We process your information only when we have a valid legal reason.
In what situations and with which parties do we share personal information? We may share information in specific situations and with specific third parties.
How do we keep your information safe? We have organizational and technical processes and procedures to protect your personal information. However, no electronic transmission over the internet or information storage technology can be guaranteed to be 100% secure, so we cannot promise or guarantee that hackers, cybercriminals, or other unauthorized third parties will not be able to defeat our security and improperly collect, access, steal.
